=begin pod

=head1 Slangify::Tutorial

B<Using Slangify with LLMs: From Prompt to Structured Output>

Suppose you want an LLM to extract structured information from messy text — but
you don't want to hand-write JSON schemas or fragile parsing logic.

Input:

=begin code
Jane booked a table for 4 at 7:30pm tomorrow at Bistro Verde
=end code

Desired output:

=begin code :lang<json>
{
  "name": "Jane",
  "party_size": 4,
  "time": "7:30 PM",
  "restaurant": "Bistro Verde",
  "date": "tomorrow"
}
=end code

Slangify lets you define that structure with a DSL, then use an LLM to populate
it reliably. This tutorial walks through everything from a first schema to a
real-world pipeline.

=head2 What you will learn

=item Understand what Slangify does
=item Define a simple DSL schema using a Raku Grammar
=item Connect it to an LLM via C<LLM::Functions>
=item Generate structured outputs from prompts
=item Validate and post-process results
=item See how this fits into a real workflow

=head2 Chapters

=item L<1. Setup|01-setup.md>
=item L<2. Your First Schema|02-schema.md>
=item L<3. Connecting to an LLM|03-llm.md>
